<DOC><DOCNO> AP880319-0122 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 1550EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-UN-Nicaragua     03-19 0206</FIRST><SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0212</SECOND><HEAD>U.N. Observer Mission Heading To Nicaragua</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A team of U.N. observers will visitNicaragua as soon as possible to investigate the border conflictwith Honduras, a U.N. spokesman said Saturday.   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar decided to send theteam at Nicaragua's request. He said it would include one politicalofficer from U.N. headquarters and an undecided number of militaryobservers, U.N. spokesman Mahbub Ahmad said.   Diplomatic sources said the team was likely to include twomilitary observers and probably would leave on Tuesday. Theobservers have not been named.   The announcement followed a Security Council meeting Fridaynight during which Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States tradedallegations over whether Sandinista troops are in Honduranterritory and who is responsible for the current conflict.   Several Latin American speakers endorsed Nicaragua's call for aneutral U.N. observer mission to visit the site of the borderclashes.   Ahmad said there are no immediate plans to visit the Honduranside of the border. Sources said no request had come from Honduras.   Nicaragua has requested a joint mission by the U.N. and theOrganization of American States to investigate the border situationand make recommendations on preventing further conflict.</TEXT></DOC>